  "prompt": "How can your remove white underarm stains from shirts?",
  "response": "White underarm stains on shirts, often caused by a combination of sweat and deodorant or antiperspirant, can be stubborn but are usually removable with the right methods. Here\u2019s how to tackle them effectively:\n\n### **1. Pre-Treat the Stains**\n   - **Lemon Juice and Salt**: Mix equal parts lemon juice and salt to form a paste. Apply it to the stained area and let it sit for 30 minutes before washing.\n   - **Vinegar Solution**: Mix 1 part white vinegar with 2 parts water. Soak the underarm area in this solution for 30 minutes before washing.\n   - **Baking Soda Paste**: Make a paste with baking soda and water, apply it to the stains, and let it sit for 15\u201330 minutes before rinsing.\n\n### **2. Wash the Shirt**\n   - Use a laundry detergent designed for stain removal.\n   - Wash the shirt in warm water (check the care label to ensure the fabric can handle it).\n   - Add a cup of white vinegar to the rinse cycle to help break down residue.\n\n### **3. Use Specific Stain Removers**\n   - Apply a stain remover or oxygen-based bleach (like OxiClean) directly to the stains and let it sit before washing.\n   - For white shirts, you can use a small amount of chlorine bleach diluted in water, but only if the fabric is bleach-safe.\n\n### **4. Prevent Future Stains**\n   - Allow deodorant or antiperspirant to dry completely before putting on clothing.\n   - Consider switching to a deodorant or antiperspirant without aluminum, which is often the culprit for yellow or white stains.\n   - Wear undershirts to absorb sweat and protect your outer clothing.\n\n### **5. For Tough Stains**\n   - If stains persist, repeat the pre-treatment process or try a commercial stain remover specifically for underarm stains.\n   - For delicate fabrics, take the shirt to a professional cleaner.\n\n### **Note**: Always test any cleaning solution on a small, inconspicuous area of the fabric first to ensure it won\u2019t cause damage or discoloration.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
